TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Design of Optimal Conservation Programs by Electric Utilities Considering Strategic Consumer Behavior
AU  - Wirl, Franz
Y1  - 1996/03/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.42.3.404
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.42.3.404
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 404
EP  - 414
VL  - 42
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The practice of utility demand side conservation programs, one of the most topical issues of utility management, provokes strategic reactions of consumers. As a solution of this moral hazard, optimal conservation programs are characterized when the consumers differ either with respect to their subjective time preference or with respect to the level of demand. In particular, we derive incentive compatible conservation schemes that mitigate strategic behavior. These incentives differ starkly from actual programs. First, the costs of conservation may exceed the avoided costs, yet accepting such high costs (at the margin) need not imply a large conservation. Second, such incentive scheme should bypass the inefficient consumers (e.g., the ?poor?) but should instead target consumers who act efficiently and have a high demand (e.g., the ?rich?).
AB  - The practice of utility demand side conservation programs, one of the most topical issues of utility management, provokes strategic reactions of consumers. As a solution of this moral hazard, optimal conservation programs are characterized when the consumers differ either with respect to their subjective time preference or with respect to the level of demand. In particular, we derive incentive compatible conservation schemes that mitigate strategic behavior. These incentives differ starkly from actual programs. First, the costs of conservation may exceed the avoided costs, yet accepting such high costs (at the margin) need not imply a large conservation. Second, such incentive scheme should bypass the inefficient consumers (e.g., the ?poor?) but should instead target consumers who act efficiently and have a high demand (e.g., the ?rich?).
